<td width="80%" valign="top"  bgcolor='#FFFFFF'> 
 <!-- #BeginEditable "Body" --> 

            <BR><center><a href='http://www.decktech.net/adserver/click.php?mgr=aspcode.net&id=36'><img border='0' src='/banner/cardagora15b.gif'  ></a></center><div class='main'><div class='mainheader'><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="178dc98989d669ff4092283ae3e60f13" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magic/articles/articles.php'>Video Games and Movies</option><option value='/wars/articles/articles.php'>Wizards Minis</option></select></td></form></tr></table></div><div class='maincontent'><font class="h1font"> THE BASICS - &quot;Standard&quot; Teams<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/heroclix/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/heroclix/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/heroclix/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/heroclix/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/heroclix/gfx/theme1/star.gif" width="19" height="18" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(5.00)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/heroclix/main/mpage.php?member=14720'>Cardagora "CardAgora.com" Admin</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/heroclix/main/mpage.php?member=14720&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> September 3, 2003</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Basic Team Archetypes<br />
You&#39;re new to Heroclix, never been to a tournament, and you&#39;re wondering what you&#39;re going to see there by way of teams.  Here are some basic team archetypes, it&#39;ll give you an idea on what to expect and will also provide some ideas on building your own teams.  Good luck!<br />
<br />
TEAM BUILDING FUNDAMENTALS<br />
These are some basic guidelines that serve me well.  We&#39;ll assume its a 300 point build.  Make sure you have a medic; medics with an &quot;8&quot; attack value on their opening click are particularly good - that means an E or V medic.  You&#39;ll also want to look closely to see if you can fit an outwit figure and (Marvel only) a probability controller (PC).  PC is essential if you&#39;re easily frustrated by poor dice rolls, or relying heavily on Blade Claws Fangs damage.  You won&#39;t be able to fit both Outwit and PC on every team, but you should consider them carefully.  Perplex is quickly becoming another &quot;must have&quot; because its so versatile.  In Marvel, that can often mean fitting in a cheapie Con Artist.<br />
<br />
How many figures?  As a general rule, make sure you have twice as many figures as actions.  For a 300 point build, 3 actions per turn, try to have at least 6 figures; its a good guideline for making sure you&#39;ll be able to take a few actions each turn without constant pushing.  Most of the time, 2 or 3 good attackers with support will be much more effective than a single, overpriced beatstick.<br />
<br />
Okay, on to the basic archetypes:<br />
<br />
MARVEL<br />
Burnt Cheese<br />
This is a basic team utilizing Firelord, a cheap taxi, and an effective medic.  Some will run dual Firelords being carried by dual E Wasps - particularly cheesie.  Be ready.  This style of play takes a big hit when the new rules go into effect, but you&#39;ll still see this team until mid-October.  It attacks hard from range and pulls the Firelords back for easy healing.  Beating Firelord effectively, on this style team, is its own article…<br />
<br />
<br />
Brick Toss<br />
&quot;Bricks&quot; are those tough-guy fighters - they tend to have super strength, damage reduction like invulnerability or toughness, and high damage capabilities (sometimes BCF -Blades Claws Fangs).  The basic idea is to build a fast, effective way to get your brick into attack position  - base to base against an opponent&#39;s main attacker - either TK w/ Charge or a long range taxi.  Good characters on this team are figures like Logan, V-Doc Samson, She-Hulk, Abomination.  Brick Toss strategies will be more prevalent with the new rules, especially featuring Chargers like Doc Samson or She-Hulk.<br />
<br />
Energy Explosion<br />
Energy Explosion is a tricky power for new people; here&#39;s the basic idea - your damage gets reduced to 1, but when you hit a figure, all the adjacent figures take a click of damage.  Abilities like Enhancement or SHIELD team, that increase damage AFTER the attack, will increase the Energy Explosion and all the splash damage.  Sounds pretty good, right?  When an Energy Exploder has multiple attack arrows, it’s often possible to hit two adjacent figures so they splash each other multiple times.  The damage can be heinous - 4 to 6 clicks to everyone caught in the crossfire splash.<br />
<br />
Popular figures in this style of team are Ultron, Boomerang, Psylocke, Doctor Strange, and even some SHIELD figures.<br />
<br />
Invisible Turtle<br />
Rookie Invisible Girl has created her own series of &quot;degenerate&quot; teams.  She has 18 Defense with Defend, meaning she can give her defense score to all the adjacent friendlies.  Couple it with some Energy Shield Deflection (ESD) figures on Hindering Terrain, and they all get a 21 defense!  Here&#39;s how:  imagine Bullseye is sitting on the building corner on an object token, with Invisible Girl behind him; she gives him an 18 defense.  Anyone shooting at Bullseye needs to deal with his +2 due to ESD, making his defense a 20.  Furthermore, the object token adds an additional +1 - voila - 21 defense - very tough to hit for most characters.<br />
<br />
The team is often played as a &#39;turtle&#39; team because the opponent will set up an advantageous ranged position and force the opponent to come to him.  Popular figures in this team are Invisible Girl (duh), and ranged ESD figures such as Bullseye, Human Torch, Storm, Deathbird, etc.  Characters with running shot can actually take Invisible Girl&#39;with them when they move, too.<br />
<br />
Invisible Turtle takes a hit in the new rules with the changes to Pulse Wave.<br />
<br />
Hit and Run<br />
Hypersonic Speed fuels this strategy; while support pieces enhance your Hypersonic character and help you play an evasive game of attack and retreat.  Hypersonic lets your attacker move in from out of range, make an attack, and keep moving.  Common strategies that go with it are Con Artists to make the Hypersonic character deal massive damage with Perplex; a barrier figure to create a safe spot, PC character&#39;s to make the Hypersonic character hard to hit, etc.  Maybe even a pulse wave character to activate the Con Artists.<br />
<br />
The limited Hypersonic figures in the game are Nightcrawler in Marvel, the various Flashes in DC, OWAW Superman, and Amazo.<br />
<br />
Super Sentinel<br />
Similar to Hit and Run in that it features Perplex, this strategy usually relies on a Pulse Wave character to damage some Con Artists on turn one, and then uses a few Con Artists to Perplex the Sentinel&#39;s stats.  Since the Sentinel has great range, Running Shot, and can attack twice per turn, it can be pretty nasty.  Occasionally you&#39;ll see the Sentinel toting around the Invisible Girl, too.<br />
<br />
An alternative Sentinel strategy (and this works for Sinestro) is to build a Mind Control team that takes control of an opponent&#39;s figure, and moves it away from the opponent&#39;s main force to where the Sentinel or Sinestro can capture it for some easy points.  Funny stuff - you&#39;ve got to love the shenanigans.<br />
<br />
Balanced Good Stuff<br />
This is an effective style of play that blends a number of strategies; it usually includes all the good support figures and powers (Outwit, Perplex, PC, and medic Support), a good ranged attacker like a Firelord or V Bullseye, and a good close combat attacker like Logan, Taskmaster, Wolverine, Sabretooth, etc.  The team is usually rounded out by a few cheap taxis, like Wasp, Vulture or Doombots.<br />
<br />
And if you can fit them in, you should always put a Ninja on your team.  Because Ninjas are cool, and by cool, I mean totally sweet.<br />
<br />
Rogue Combos<br />
Then there&#39;s the kooky stuff - the combo stuff.  I think this is the funnest style of play, and encourage you to develop unusual combos.  One of my favorites involves E Whirlwind and a strong Wildcard Attacker (like Taskmaster) - when they&#39;re adjacent, Whirlwind can borrow Taskmaster&#39;s attack value by sharing the Sinister Syndicate ability.  Perplex Whirlwind&#39;s damage a few times and he&#39;s a force to be reckoned with!  You just need a few good taxis to get them in position.  (Good old Doombots).<br />
<br />
Other things you&#39;ll see are dual mind control teams (Moondragon and E White Queen are good for it) and heavy Super Senses teams with extra Probability Controllers to make each attack frustrating.<br />
<br />
<br />
DC Variants<br />
Up until the release of Cosmic Justice, DC was pretty boring - now it’s my favorite format!  Previously, you basically saw Bat Teams vs Brick Teams or Balanced Teams; DC didn&#39;t have enough combos and kookiness to support a lot of diversity.  The introduction of new powers and the Legion of Superheroes (DC Wildcards) changed all that.<br />
<br />
Bat Team<br />
The Bat Team is very potent; all of the batman allies have permanent stealth due to the team ability, freeing up their movement slot for leap climb; most of them have it down the dial.  This makes them very difficult to tie down; they can’t be ranged and they can always break away when based.  Additionally, the two most popular figures (E Batman, V Nightwing) have healthy doses of outwit and good damage.  Maybe that&#39;s why you see one or the other on every tournament team?  Hmmmm.<br />
<br />
Anyway, a popular style of play is to use an all-stealth or mostly stealth with ranged attackers featuring Batman, Nightwing, Huntress and Robin.  Occasionally the team will run a few effective taxis, the best ones in DC are Hawkman and Booster Gold for their price.  Expect to see this team a lot.<br />
<br />
Beatdown<br />
Just like the Brick Toss, DC has had an effective beatdown strategy.  In DC the beatstick of choice is usually Bane, often being taxied by an E Manbat, who can borrow Bane&#39;s attack sharing the Batman Enemy team.   Typically this team would run a Nightwing or Batman as a secondary attacker, with another taxi, and then some support.<br />
<br />
Wildcards<br />
The Legion of Superheroes has turned DC on its head.  The DC team abilities are quite a bit more powerful, so building a wildcard team ability into DC has made the Legionnaires into champs.  First off, they slide right into the Bat Team as they can borrow stealth at will – at the minimum, you’ll see them picking up stealth tricks from Huntress or Robin.  The next three team styles all take advantage of the wild card ability to fuel a strategy.<br />
<br />
I can remember laughing out loud when I saw that DC actually had characters named &quot;Saturn Girl&quot;, &quot;Cosmic Boy&quot;, and &quot;Lightning Lad&quot; – (actually Livewire in the Clix game.)  Could it get any cornier?  But let me tell you, they&#39;re worth their weight in gold as Clix figures.<br />
<br />
Mystics<br />
This team uses a Mystic (Circe, Mordru, Zatanna) to give all the Wildcards the Mystic ability.  If the wild cards get put into harms way, they’ll deal damage back each time they&#39;re hit by copying the Mystics.  Of course, make sure you have a cheap Robin or Huntress so they can fire from stealth.  Their dials aren&#39;t terribly deep.<br />
<br />
Green Lantern Swarm<br />
This team features the Batman Enemy ability, a Rookie Green Lantern, and a Wildcard to borrow the Green Lantern ability.  With two Green Lanterns, you can move your whole team around the board in one turn.  With the Batman Enemy, all your characters can share attack values, which is very effective if the Wildcard is Saturn Girl, as she perplexes her attack (or Bane&#39;s attack) up to a 10 or 11, and everyone can borrow it!  It’s common to see a Rookie Aquaman out there for his cheap leadership, since the extra action is important.<br />
<br />
Wizkids recently changed the tournament rules, to say that you couldn’t attack the opponent in their starting area on turn 1, before they had an opportunity to move.  I think a big part of the reason Wizkids changed rule to disallow the first turn strike was because of how devastating was the first turn double Green Lantern - you could prevent the opponent from moving his figures at all.<br />
<br />
Meta Counter<br />
Rooke Steel, with his relatively cheap Superman Ally team, fuels a common DC counter team; using Rookie Steel and some ranged Wildcards to see the stealthed figures and attack from range.  Naturally, you use your own Bat team members so your Wildcards are themselves stealthed and unrangeable- very nasty.<br />
<br />
----------------------<br />
<br />
All right!  Hope that gives you some good ideas, feel free to D-mail me if you want to see a specific build to demonstrate one of these guys.<br />
